      "span_text": "Although definite cause of chordae tendineae rupture remains confusing, primary rupture is thought to be more frequent cause than the other underlying situations such as mitral valve prolapse, subacute bacterial endocarditis, local myxomatous degeneration, rheumatic heart disease (mostly during the chronic stage), systemic or generalized connective tissue abnormality (such as in Marfan syndrome, osteogenesis imperfecta, and Ehler-Danlos syndrome), blunt chest trauma, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, other (nonmitral) heart and valvular abnormalities (such as aortic stenosis and aortic regurgitation), ischemic heart disease in general, and myocardial infarction in particular [CITATION_1] ."
